 DHS has not answered detailed questions from the AP about the use of the WRAP and did not respond to a request for comment Thursday. DHS spokesperson Tricia McLaughlin previously said that ICE’s practices “align with those followed by other relevant authorities and is fully in line with established legal standards.” The manufacturer of the WRAP, Safe Restraints Inc., said in a statement to AP that the device “was specifically designed to prevent pain and injury.”  “Our priority is preserving life and preventing harm,” the company said. “We strongly oppose any misuse or untrained use of this equipment.” The AP found that DHS has paid Safe Restraints Inc. $268,523 since it started purchasing the devices in late 2015, during the Obama administration. Government purchasing records show the two Trump administrations have been responsible for about 91% of that spending.  ICE would not provide AP with records documenting its use of the WRAP despite multiple requests, and it’s not clear how frequently it has been used in the current and prior administrations. 



